    <a title="Eesha" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/100154682-eesha"><img alt="Eesha" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2903345978?book_show_action=true">Jul 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eesha" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eesha" href="/user/show/100154682-eesha">Eesha</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/51102530-the-real-happiness">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2903345978" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12161076942931116863">I came across this book through a recommendation from a friend, and I’m extremely thankful for this gesture. I read the book all at once, I must say it had me hypnotized to the core. <br/>It is an edgy exploration of faith and true love. The author has phrased some very pure feelings into words for this script. A very unique factor in the book is that the characters are presented very strongly in their roles even though they aren’t given any name. It is quite interesting how anonymity is used to expl</span>
  <span id="freeText12161076942931116863" style="display:none">I came across this book through a recommendation from a friend, and I’m extremely thankful for this gesture. I read the book all at once, I must say it had me hypnotized to the core. <br />It is an edgy exploration of faith and true love. The author has phrased some very pure feelings into words for this script. A very unique factor in the book is that the characters are presented very strongly in their roles even though they aren’t given any name. It is quite interesting how anonymity is used to explain certain things here. <br />The next key element is the integration of another story enduring somewhere else with a completely different style yet entirely cohesive with the afore stated account. The relation created amongst each section deserves quite a lot of praise. <br />The design of the book is intriguing as it withholds the essence of true love, the charm of aspiring friendships and most importantly the firm standing upon one’s own intuitive beliefs. It seems to be a different book, focusing on morally valued incentives rather than the customary. While reading the book, I found true happiness and a lot of peace; knowing how it ended. <br />My favorite quote from the book would definitely be: Yes, the doings of nature are slow but well-timed, prayers with no bad for anyone in it and prayers spoken out of the depth of the heart are always heard but they are not usually fulfilled the way you want but in the best of the best ways. <br />If words may be something which bring peace to you, this book is a must read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12161076942931116863" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


